At the beginning of 2021, an assessment was carried out to identify in-demand technical professions among residents of the pilot districts. The results of the assessment identified the main professions most popular among young people: plumber, seamstress/tailor, electric and gas welder, electrician, pastry chef, information technology specialist, etc. Vocational training was conducted for [30] rural women in target districts where the participants increased technical skills on cooking, received diplomas, [16] girls started working in various areas of service delivery, including tourism and hotel services;

A wool processing workshop and the manufacture of woolen/felt products are established in Muynak district at the remote Ali aul community, where [10] women/girls are employed. The workshop serves as a platform for rural women and girls to improve their practical knowledge and skills on this craft, help to increase family income, promote the revival of traditional crafts and develop tourism sector in the region; 

[30] young men from the youth notebook obtained theoretical and practical skills of a plumber with the qualification of a 3-class plumber. Each trained participant was given a necessary 30 sets of tools which will contribute to the professional development of young people. [21] youth are employed (formal/informal) and increasing their family income;

In 3 target regions, Mono-Centers for vocational training of unemployed youth, women and migrants of the Aral Sea region are being created, relevant tools and equipment being procured and renovation work is being implemented;

A startup platform is being created in cooperation with Agency for Youth Affairs of Karakalpakstan (Youth Center in Nukus). Necessary equipment, are being purchased, completion is expected by mid of 2022;

Startup training initiated in 2021 in the field of environment, IT, social, tourism, agriculture and climate change for [72] participants (18-30 years old) from 3 pilot districts and Nukus. Training will continue until March 2022, including mentorship, project development. Upon completion, contest will be organized among start-uppers and winners will be provided financial support;


At the beginning of 2021, an assessment was carried out to identify in-demand technical professions among residents of the pilot districts. The results of the assessment identified the main professions most popular among young people: plumber, seamstress/tailor, electric and gas welder, electrician, pastry chef, information technology specialist, etc. Vocational training was conducted for [30] rural women in target districts where the participants increased technical skills on cooking, received diplomas, [16] girls started working in various areas of service delivery, including tourism and hotel services;

A wool processing workshop and the manufacture of woolen/felt products are established in Muynak district at the remote Ali aul community, where [10] women/girls are employed. The workshop serves as a platform for rural women and girls to improve their practical knowledge and skills on this craft, help to increase family income, promote the revival of traditional crafts and develop tourism sector in the region; 

[30] young men from the youth notebook obtained theoretical and practical skills of a plumber with the qualification of a 3-class plumber. Each trained participant was given a necessary 30 sets of tools which will contribute to the professional development of young people. [21] youth are employed (formal/informal) and increasing their family income;

In 3 target regions, Mono-Centers for vocational training of unemployed youth, women and migrants of the Aral Sea region are being created, relevant tools and equipment being procured and renovation work is being implemented;

A startup platform is being created in cooperation with Agency for Youth Affairs of Karakalpakstan (Youth Center in Nukus). Necessary equipment, are being purchased, completion is expected by mid of 2022;

Startup training initiated in 2021 in the field of environment, IT, social, tourism, agriculture and climate change for [72] participants (18-30 years old) from 3 pilot districts and Nukus. Training will continue until March 2022, including mentorship, project development. Upon completion, contest will be organized among start-uppers and winners will be provided financial support. 



[110] women from Kungrat (45), Buzatau (31) and Muynak (34) districts improved their knowledge of home-based/individual entrepreneurship in three-day trainings held in three districts of Karakalpakstan. 

Competition-fair on presentations of business ideas organized in Nukus. 20 business ideas submitted by participants from 3 districts. A selection committee was organized, consisting of representatives of district branches of mahalla and family support, representatives of UNDP, UNFPA and expert trainers. Based on the results of the evaluation, the selection committee proposed [13] projects (Bozatau - 6; Muynak - 6 and Kungrad - 1) for financial support.

[18] community leaders for the local communities were trained to promote and expand the economic rights of women (8 from Kundrad; 5 from Bozatau and 5 from Muynak) in close coordination with the Ministry of Mahalla and Family Support of Karakalpakstan;


Research on environmental protection of Aral Sea region fostering innovative solutions to rehabilitate and upgrade the existing irrigation system and agricultural land restoration is envisioned to be conducted in 2022-2023.


2.2 FAO portfolio 

[3] youth cooperatives have been established. Agricultural equipment is being supplied to two cooperatives (Muynak and Bozatau) that are engaged in the cultivation of sesame, wheat, corn and poultry farming. Fruit trees have been planted on 2 ha of land and a well has been drilled for watering the garden of the cooperative (Kungrad). Technical support is being provided for 3 cooperatives and expected to be fully procured in 1st quarter of 2022. These projects will create over 100 new jobs among young people;
Technical support is being provided to the International Innovation Center for Aral Sea Basin under President of Uzbekistan (IICAS), in creation of demonstration plots on innovative resource-saving methods of agriculture Buried diffuser . Installation, testing on demonstration plots is planned for spring and summer 2022. Youth, farmers, dehkans will obtain knowledge on innovative resource-saving technologies. In the demonstration plots, it is planned to use two irrigation system technologies Buried Diffuser Technology and Drip irrigation;
[6] vulnerable households wishing to engage in agricultural activities were selected from the “iron notebook”, jointly with the district khokimiyats. 4 - in the field of vegetable growing (greenhouses, drip irrigation equipment), 1 - orchard 0.36 ha (seedlings, drip irrigation equipment) and 1- solar-powered poultry incubator. Greenhouses installed. An orchard has been planted. In spring, a drip system is expected to be installed in greenhouses and an orchard. Incubator in the process of delivery;

Community mobilization trainings conducted with the participation of 279 residents of nine communities and 9 Community Development Plans (CDPs) developed. Design estimates for 6 priority projects have been developed;
[4] projects on access to clean drinking water have been successfully completed in Kungrad and Bozatau districts. Water supply networks were constructed in 2 health facilities in Suenli community and district central hospital. Water supply network is constructed in 2 secondary schools sanitation and hygiene conditions were improved in two medical institutions and two secondary schools with the installation of a solar water heater; 
[2] water purification equipment installed in Kazakhdarya and Koksu communities (10 kb/h);
[17] projects on access to sustainable electricity have been successfully completed in 3 districts;
[3] projects on empowerment of vulnerable remote communities through the use of modern digital technologies. 3 schools were procured with ICT to provide access to internet and digitalization;

